div1.p:
I have the Honor to State that Clearing a Vessel from Port is a perplexing operation. 1st notice of eight things must be given, 2nd a Bond with two sureities (merchants) in the sum of Four Thousand Mil Reis Fracos $2.675.59 must be entered into as a guarantee that the vessel will not engage in the Slave Trade.
Page 2
This is well, when suspicion attaches to any vessel, but it is exacted indiscriminately, previous to granting a Clearance, not that there is any fear that a well known vessel will engage in the Slave Trade, but that the merchants who sign the bond may realize the Fee which is forty five pound or One hundred and twenty five Dollars for so doing;

The Practice is continued (I am told) in accordance
with an inference drawn from a Law of 1836 there
being no positive law to justify it;
